I used to curl. It is harder than it looks. You have a Teflon side on one shoe to give you slide on the ice when you curl your stone. The stone is 40lbs and you have to control where it is going in a target across the ice with wrist movements and how fast you move on the ice as you curl it. Then when you are the sweeper, which is the job of the 1st two curlers, you are moving fast up and down the ring with your skip(team captain) telling where to sweep to direct the stone, plus after a few rounds the ice gets groves so you are trying to correct that to get the stone in the center of th e target.  Your legs burn at the end of a match, your arms hurt and you are sweaty.  It is a work out. I played college softball and curled and I sweated more and hurt more curling.
